05218nam a22006375i 9780773566019DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19961996xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735660197 a10.1515/97807735660192doi  a(DE-B1597)655232  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aNA1bC46 1994 vol. 2eb 7aARC0000002bisacsh04a720/.11 aPérez-Gómez, Alberto, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChora 2 :bIntervals in the Philosophy of Architecture /cStephen Parcell, Alberto Pérez-Gómez. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1996] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCHORA: Intervals in the Philosophy of Architecture ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tSocrates in the Agora -- tOn the Use of Architecture: The Destination of Buildings Revisited -- tHermes' Laugh: Philibert de 1’Orme’s Imagery as a Case of Analogical Edification -- tThe Angel and the Mirror: Reflections on the Architecture of the Amalgam -- tLessons of a Dream -- tArchitecture as Site of Reception.Part II: Sea-Food and Vampires1 -- tConcrete Blonde: A Probe into Negative Space where Mysteries are Created -- tSurrealist Paris: The Non-Perspectival Space of the Lived City -- tThe Metaphoric Architecture of the Diorama -- tThe Legend of the Golem -- tParadoxical Spaces in Literature, Film and Architecture: A Dialogue with Alain Robbe-Grillet -- tWhen the Old Mirror is not yet Polished, What Would You Say of it? -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKarsten Harries provides a new and long-overdue reading of Martin Heidegger's well-known essay "Building Dwelling Thinking." Donald Kunze and Stephen Parcell consider possibilities of meaningful architectural space for a visual culture, continuing themes they addressed in Chora 1. Further reflections on the spaces of literature, cinema, and architecture include an interview with French writer and film maker Alain Robbe-Grillet and articles by Dagmar Motycka Weston on the surrealist city, Tracey Eve Winton on the museum as a paradigmatic modern building, and Terrance Galvin on spiritual space in the works of Jean Cocteau. Jean-Pierre Chupin and Bram Ratner explore historical themes in their essays on French Renaissance architect Philibert de l'Orme and the Jewish myth of the Golem. Gregory Caicco addresses ethical questions in his essay on the Greek agora and the death of Socrates, as does Lily Chi in her meditation on the critical issue of use in architectural works. A concern with architectural representation and generative strategies for the making of architecture is present throughout, especially in the essay by Joanna Merwood on the provocative House by British artist Rachel Whiteread.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArchitecturexPhilosophy. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh1 aChi, Lily H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChupin, Jean-Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalvin, Terrance, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarries, Karsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKunze, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerwood, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMotycka Weston, Dagmar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParcell, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aParcell, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaul Caicco, Gregory, econtributor.4c